column22: The SIL had some good activities, including practice questions and a brain dump. column22: The SI should have an opener to get students warmed up to the session and get to know each other. The students were also all sitting down in a lecture style spread throughout the room. I would have either students stand up and be on the whiteboard or join desks and make a group table to facilitate collaboration.  There were only 2 activities done in the session: 1) having students describe econ topics and 2) having students guess his hangman words. The students were sitting down the whole time, and a variety of activities would have served a more variety of learning styles.
column33: The SI leader had a great session atmosphere. He knew students' names and the session atmosphere was very laid back. The students seemed very comfortable with him. However, he was mostly talking and directing the session to one student, and the other two were not as engaged. The other two students seemed more shy, but he never made an effort to incorporate them in the session. It is critical to make an effort to connect with ALL students, not just one!
column35: There was no closer. After the hangman activity (where SIL held the marker the whole time and the students guessed the word), some of the students asked questions about the class, and the students left.
column36: You did a really good job learning and using students’ names, which made the session feel more personal. The atmosphere was great, and students seemed comfortable participating. I liked how you used candy as an incentive; it was a fun way to market and get students engaged. You also redirected questions really well to get students thinking, and you gave good wait time so they had space to work through their answers.
column37:
It would help to make the opener and closer more clear, since the session felt like it started a bit abruptly and ended without a clear wrap-up. Putting the agenda on the board at the beginning would also give students a sense of what to expect.

One of the main areas for improvement is making the session more collaborative. For example, instead of running the hangman game yourself, you could have students create the words and quiz each other. Another simple change would be letting students take turns holding the marker rather than keeping it yourself. This would encourage more active participation and make the session feel more student-led.

I also noticed that most of the participation came from one student (in the red shirt), while the other two were focused on other work. You can always remind students to stay engaged and try to draw them in by asking them directly or by assigning them small roles during the activity.

column22:
Areas of Strength:
The vocab grab bag was a great way to get the students involved in discussion and starting to think about the material. It also helps the students feel more comfortable with each other.   After they finished solving a problem, the SIL did a good job having them explain their solution to check their understanding. While solving, the SIL wasn't hovering over them or telling them the answer
Areas of Improvement:
When the students ask you questions, redirect it to the group so the other can answer their question or they can discuss to try to connect the dots. If applicable, have them refer to their notes before giving more hints or explaining yourself. When they're working together to solve the problems, don't jump in to give hints or point out mistakes until after they're finished solving or have exhausted all other resources to figure things out.
Reorganize the room before the students come in so that the room doesn't feel like a random jumble of desks where the students can sit anywhere. It's a bit too chaotic.
column33:
Areas of Strength:
The students were fully involved in the activity. By switching out who wrote the code on the board every line, the SI Leader made sure the students were actively remembering what came next. The students seemed very comfortable with the SIL and each other. The SIL wrote no code herself and only pointed out mistakes if the students didn't catch them themselves.
Areas of Improvement:
Try to use their names and give some praise throughout the session when they answer correctly. When the students are confused or have a question, before redirecting them, encourage them to ask each other, discuss, or look at their notes if applicable.

column36: You did a great job making sure the session was student-led, checking for understanding, and ensuring all the students were actively learning. You did a good job of asking a question to hint towards the solution instead of giving the solution when the students asked questions.
column37: When the students have questions, redirect it to the group before answering yourself and have them look at their notes before giving more hints or explaining. Also, when they're solving problems, leave them to solve the problems without hints or pointing out mistakes until they've completed the problem or exhausted their resources in figuring it out. Try to use their names more.

This was a super strong session!! You used many collaborative learning activities and checked for understanding consistently throughout your session. I can tell that even though it is still early in the semester, you have fostered a great relationship with your students - they were all engaged and participated a lot. You are super strong in immediately redirecting questions asked to other students, allowing them to use each other as a resource. I also really love how you and SIL bounced back and forth together to check in with the pairs of students when they were working at whiteboards.

Another thing I really loved is that you didn't make your students feel bad or feel embarrassed if they didn't know the material. You were super patient with the girl in the red sweater when she totally didn't understand atomic orbitals - really great job redirecting to the rest of the students and allowing them to continue that conversation together. I can tell that your students aren't afraid to mess up or make mistakes and that is a true testament to you as a person and how you run your sessions.

column22:
Strengths: The room was arranged in table groups when I came in which is great for collaboration! SIL has such a friendly and kind vibe and I can tell that her students feel comfortable to ask her questions and participate, which they did. She did a longer opener today, but set a great boundary for the students for how much time they could take on it before they moved on - which I think is super important because the opener that she did was super fun and sometimes it can take a lot of effort to get students to start focusing on content. The two main activities SIL did was a worksheet and make-a-quizlet. The students and SIL did the first half of the worksheet together, then the students finished it in their table groups and went over it altogether. The make-a-quizlet activity is SO great for photo tech - the students did this in clusters and it is awesome because it lets them literally make their own study resource while in session that they can refer back to later. 

Improvements: There were only 9 students present, and sometimes with lower numbers, it makes it more awkward to walk around, but I do think she could have been a little more active, especially when going over the worksheet. Something I liked to do when I was a SIL was sit on one of the tables or just stand away from the podium in general when going over worksheets! This helped me feel more involved and not like I was lecturing the material to the students, so maybe this is something she could try.
column33:
Strengths: SIL did great incorporating the one student that came in late!! She caught them up right away and had them pull up a chair to one of the tables. The balance between her and SIL was also really strong throughout the session - they were bouncing off of each other and it was great to see. She knows and used most of the students' names (I think there were a few new people and the students were a little unsure who each other were). She did great with this though, reminding students of each other's names.

Improvements: Kind of going off of my last sentence, SIL is on the quieter side, so it is definitely a little easier for Audrey to kind of take control of the session if the students get distracted or start side conversations. I know this will come with time, but I would like to see SIL taking charge a little bit more of her sessions!! Having a co-lead is great because you can lean on each other throughout the session, but I want to encourage her to be more confident and own her sessions! Also, I think that sometimes when students are having a hard time with the material, it can really help to almost OVER praise them for their contributions. It didn't seem like she had any students who were 100% lost, but this was just kind of a general comment for future sessions because the material will get really confusing later in the semester.
column35: They played Quizlet live with the Quizlet they just made in their table groups! So much fun and such a great way to keep the session flowing.
column36: This was a super chill session and you did really well!! You also had such great energy throughout the session and the students definitely matched that. Your sessions have been super strong so far and I have loved reading your paperwork; I can't wait to see how much you grow throughout the semester!!
column37: Being super nitpicky because you did awesome - you could use the students' names a little more! They all seemed really comfortable so this wasn't a huge issue but it just helps them feel more welcomed when you use their names directly. One thing I also noticed is that while you were reviewing the TOD worksheet with them, you tended to stand behind the podium a lot. Even just sitting on the table next to the podium or something like that can help make reviewing the worksheet less lecturey and more like a conversation - like you're all just casually talking about TOD together! LOL if that makes any sense. Overall such a good job though!!

column36: I like that the room was set up collaboratively and you encouraged students to sit towards the front. The students seemed comfortable chatting about the classes they were stressed about etc which is great. The content review was productive and all the students were engaged.
column37: I would suggest showing up to your session a few minutes early so you can make sure the room is set up how you want it, you have your agenda on the board, SI materials ready, etc. If it's a recurring theme for students to show up late I would understand why you also show up right on time for sessions, but in general you should be a few minutes early. I would also suggest writing the agenda in more detail - for my sessions I'll write "opener" and then provide a few words description of what the opener is. This helps students understand what to expect or what they're doing when they show up late. I do like that you included the approximate timing for each of the activities on the agenda though! Finally, I would try and wrap up sessions on time since there's another session after yours.

I additionally would have liked to see more question redirection; for example there were some times you pointed out what a student did right/wrong/“here’s another way he could have done this” and this would have been a great opportunity to ask the rest of the group “What’s another way he could have done this?”

column5:
* The session plan was strong overall, keeping students engaged in group work. In particular, I liked how the first half served as a refresher and the second half worked as a comprehensive check for understanding, with a gradual increase in difficulty that built on prior material.

* The closing check-in on exam readiness is a great strategy to get to understand how your students feel about an upcoming exam and find out what topics you might want to cover. The SI could maybe incorporate some more into this section. For example, a Google form to get people's feelings anonymously, and or could incorporate a discussion on possible study habits.  

* The SI is very self-reflective and has adopted the SI model well. During the mock activity, all facilitation strategies were used.

* Marketing is solid, but could be strengthened by promoting sessions in the lab to the entire class and incorporating a possible reward system. What really stood out to me was that the SI is already engaging with, building connections, and promoting SI outside of class time, which is fantastic to hear.
column6: During coaching the SI brought up plenty of ideas. In specific, they felt it was hard to find old SI material for session ideas. I directed them to some old resources in SIShare, but it's definitely hard to find some of this material and or add onto it from their perspective.

column5: The session plan was very well thought out. The Kahoot would allow them to both practice and explain their understanding of it to each other. Altogether, it's a great session plan. column6:
She sends emails, writes reminders on board, asks professors for announcements, and mingles with students during workshops.
She won't give additional materials as incentive for session attendance because they already have ungraded homeworks that they don't do.
She speaks with the professor about what to focus/how to focus on topics during the session when she has any confusion or wants guidance.
We discussed a student who isn't participating in group activities. I suggested trying to speak with them about it and remind them to participate in the activities and address any concerns they might have. Also, using a group-based activity for the opener or closer might create a more comfortable environment in which they might feel more at-ease participating in.
Altogether, she's doing great with marketing and reaching out to students. My only suggestion is that she check in with more students in the class either in-person or through a form to see what they want out of the sessions or why they aren't coming to sessions now.
(This is right after the exam which may be why attendance dropped.)

column9: Study Habits
column10: Group discussion, Round Robin, Group survey
column22: Nothing to negative here, the SI used many different strategies, integrated study habits right into the session, and for any subject included many different ways of visualizing and understanding the same information. Very student led, and checked for understanding by passing the marker between the two students. In particular had one student come up with an example and another to solve it to check for understanding. The only small thing I can think of, is that the agenda was not displayed.
column33: Once again, really nothing too much to comment on negative. Very positive, excited, and reassuring. She incorporated students that we're a bit more quiet, got to know and used names, and adapted the session to what the students felt they were not comfortable with.
column35: Recap / Check in
column36:
* Used all facilitation strategies well. In particular, checking for understanding via two students by having one create an example, then the other solve it.

* If the wait time or the redirect doesn't work, the SI would have them go through their notes, which promotes good note-taking and allows them to find a template they can use for problems.

* The SI was very reassuring, excited, and approachable.

* Throughout the session, the SI used a variety of learning methods, such as whiteboard and paper activities, and introduced many ways to interpret the information, such as visually with the number line or metaphorically, such as bleach on a carrot. Even the idea of showing a dance to remember the sign flip was extremely clever to help them remember.

* I think my favorite thing has to be the use of the boardwalk model. It showed the students a study habit and centered the session around it. At the start, the SI asked what areas they felt comfortable and not so comfortable in, which is a great way to adjust your session as needed, i.e, focus on areas the students are struggling with more than others. Then, on top of that, the model allows them once again to internalize the information in many ways (example/template, core knowledge, the math steps, and the "narrative steps")
column37: Nothing too much to say here

column9: Hangman! They also adjusted the word to the student's comfort level
column22: Great job guiding the student through the practice problems; I know it's especially difficult when there's only one student who doesn't like to take initiative, so she did a good job being a little more generous with hints but I would still advise asking more questions or redirecting to notes since the student did have his notes out.
column33: Basically perfect job at being understanding welcoming from what I could see. She was very patient and respectful toward the student. The main area of improvement would only still be that I'd recommend giving them more time to figure things out on their own.
column35: She planned a story train but the student wanted to leave early so she gave him the choice to do that or go over the quiz.
column36: Super patient and respectful, great job guiding them through with a pace that worked for the student. And also nice job with adapting to a student who isn't super responsive; she kept it at a great energy level throughout.
column37: Since there isn't another student to redirect to, feel free to ask them to bring their notes up to the board with them and redirect to that! Also, these are general reminders, but have the name of your content activity in the agenda too and make sure to plan it to end ten minutes before the hour! column9: SIL did the Wordle for his opener - a classic.
column22:
Strengths: SIL had a really strong session despite only having one student. It can be hard when you plan for collaborative activities and only have one student show up, but he did a great job adapting his session. Joe did a function vs constant activity that I really enjoyed. He would put a function or constant up on the board and the student had to move to a side of the room based off of if they thought it was a function or constant. I liked that this activity was active! It got the student up and moving and I can definitely see how it would be fun with more students - they would have to debate their answers if they disagreed and it would be a good way to check for understanding. 

Improvements: It is tricky to have only one student show up! It makes it a lot harder to redirect questions and doesn't leave a lot of room for collaboration but I think Joe did a really good job adapting to this. A suggestion I have for Joe is to utilize wait time a little more. The student tended to ask him many questions and Joe often answered them right away, which kind of makes sense because the student definitely wanted an answer right away. Wait time is hard because it can feel awkward, but it gets students in the habit of not expecting an answer right away.
column33:
Strengths: I loved SIL's relationship with the student that attended! I got the sense that the student that attended was a regular and they had a great vibe, especially when doing the opener! Joe did well with checking for understanding and is getting better at redirection and wait time. His session environment is really great and I wish that his attendance was higher. He shows a lot of potential as a SIL and I know that his sessions would be a lot stronger with more than one student present!

Improvements: n/a here!
column36:
I loved your relationship with the students that attended! Your session environment is really strong and welcoming; if I was a calc student, I would love to come to your sessions. You did well with checking for understanding and are getting better at redirection and wait time. You show a lot of potential as a SIL and I believe that your sessions would be a lot stronger with more students present!

I also really liked how you had the girl explain the activity to the student that came in half an hour late. You did a great job incorporating the latecomer to your session - I wish he had come on time so you could have done the first activity with more than one student! Your checking for understanding at the end of the session was super strong as well.
column37:
I would encourage you to utilize wait time a little more! The girl that attended definitely seems to be used to getting answers right away, though she did catch on to you redirecting the questions haha. Don't be afraid to really use wait time to make students think a little deeper, or redirect them to their notes too (good job doing this in session). If you redirect students to their notes and they don't have many or any notes at all, it would be a great opportunity to chat with your students about study strategies and how they are taking notes!

Also, I noticed that in the second activity that you did, the student that came in late was a little lost. I know the point of the activity was for it to be a race, but in a situation like this where one student knows most of the information and another student doesn't, it might have been beneficial to pair them up and just have them work through the problem together. You did a great job of checking for understanding with the latecomer though - having him walk you back through the problem was perfect.

column35: practice problems
column36:
* Very good relationships with the students, knows names, and consistently hypes them up. Very small but letting students know it's okay if they're wrong/guess and hyping them up after they get a correct answer, goes a long way in boosting their confidence. 

* Demonstrated facilitation skills beautifully when addressing a confused student: broke problems into manageable parts, redirected questions, and consistently checked for understanding. To really highlight one, check for understanding was done amazingly. 

* Created a welcoming and supportive environment where students felt comfortable and excited to participate.

* Kept the session highly student-centered, rarely holding the marker and allowing students to lead the activity.
column37:
* Very small, but consider keeping the door propped open before and during the start of the session to make it easier and less intimidating for students to enter.

* After an exam, opening with heavy content may feel overwhelming. Having a more lighthearted opening can be a good way for students to breathe and decompress after an exam. If you really want to do something content-based instead, a debrief or group discussion about the exam could provide a smoother transition before resuming content review.

* Incorporating more variety into activities could better address diverse learning styles. Simply doing base practice problems might not work for everyone. For example, intermixing graphs and exercises might help people who are more visual learn better and give them different strategies to tackle problems in place of pattern recognition.

column9: Discussion
column10: Group discussion, Turn to a partner
column22: The SI uses check for understanding quite often and kept the session student led. Instead of Kahoot being an individual activity, the SI took advantage of only having 2 people and made it a group solving activity. However the SI could use some more redirection and wait time.
column33: The SI had a good relationship with the students and kept the session interactive throughout the whole thing.
column35: Unclear
column36:
* The session was very student-led; students were consistently engaged at the whiteboard or interacting with each other. The SI also maintained a strong relationship with them.

* The SI frequently checked for understanding and followed up with questions.

* The SI adapted well to having only two students by turning the Kahoot into a partner activity.

* Beginning with a brief discussion was a great way to gauge students’ needs and adjust the session accordingly. This may seem simple, but it's a great way to build rapport with students and gauge areas of focus during the session.
column37:
* Consider providing more redirection to the group rather than giving answers or first steps. Even with one student, rephrasing questions back (e.g., “What's your gut telling you?” and “Why do you think that?”) encourages critical thinking. Similarly, if a student finishes a problem and it's wrong, asking them to double-check or reflect before confirming or denying can be a helpful nudge.

* When a student arrived late, the SI gave them a separate problem. An alternative could be having the current student explain their thought process so far, or assigning different problems briefly before regrouping to share solutions (presentation style). This maintains collaboration while easing the transition.

* A small point: standing behind the podium and looking at your laptop at times created some distance during whiteboard problems. Sitting or standing with students may foster a more peer-friendly atmosphere.

column9: Check in
column22: The SI uses redirection and checking for understanding quite well and makes sure to keep the session student led. However, could use some more variety and wait time.

* The SI consistently used strong facilitation strategies such as redirection and checking for understanding. In particular, the SI had the student walk through her code piece by piece, verifying each part before having them generalize it for understanding.

column9: SIL did a super fun Buzzfeed quiz for her opener!
column22:
Strengths: For the first activity, SIL had 3 whiteboards up around the room full of questions that were a recap from previous sessions. She did a great job of bouncing between the groups and checking in with them. It also looked like she had the correct answers on her iPad as she was walking around, and I think that's super smart to have that material readily available if students have questions. The students collaborated really well together and SIL did a great job of encouraging that collaboration. She then checked for understanding and transitioned into new material effortlessly - I really loved the balance of focus between new and old material.

Improvements: I think that SIL's redirection could be a little stronger! She utilized checking for understanding and wait time really well, but I would have liked to see her redirect questions to other students in the group, rather than jumping in herself. I'm being picky though because all other aspects of her session were so strong!
column33:
Strengths: I read SIL's paperwork this semester, but haven't gotten the chance to observe a session of hers until now and I'm so glad I was able to! Her and SIL have a great dynamic throughout the session and the session environment is so welcoming. Although on the quieter side, SIL definitely takes control of the room and she was able to keep the students' attention span focused for the entirety of the session - I didn't see any students getting distracted or having side conversations. This is awesome! I also really enjoyed that SIL encouraged the students to read the questions carefully while they were practicing converting grams to moles and moles to grams. I really loved the cookie analogy that was given when they were reviewing limiting reagents. I think that no matter what content is being reviewed, a real life analogy can always help students understand the material better if they are struggling. 

Improvements: SIL had an idea about halfway through the session to switch up the groups of students a little bit and have them go up to the whiteboard instead of working with mini whiteboards at their table groups. I think this was a really great change to make based on how the session was going. I would have maybe liked to see this idea come from SIL instead, but honestly it's not that big of a deal because they are co-leads for a reason!! Sometimes all it takes to change the vibe of the session is to switch the groups up. Regardless though, SIL and SIL have a great relationship and I loved watching them bounce off of each other throughout the session.
column35: SIL had the students do a KWL for the closer. A great way to check for understanding!!
column36: SIL, this was a great collaborative session queen! I loved how attentive you were to the students throughout the session and I loved that the students gave their full attention to you and SIL. Your session environment is so welcoming and if I was taking chem I would be at all your sessions!! It was awesome to finally observe one of your sessions after reading your paperwork all semester. You did a really great job of walking your students through each step of the problems slowly without overwhelming them and I love that you encouraged them to read all the questions fully. You checked for understanding effortlessly and also did a really great job with wait time. I also really loved watching you and SIL bounce off each other throughout the session. Amazing job queen!!
column37: My only note would be to redirect your questions a little more! It seemed like you were answering a lot of the students' questions right off the bat, so it might be good to redirect to other students in the table groups before answering - even if no one knows the answer! It's just good to at least see if anyone else has a guess or wants to try to answer before you jump in. Not a big deal at all though - just something I noticed!! You're doing a great job!!

column9: The session was opened with obscure facts
column22:
Areas of Strength:
The SIL promoted collaboration by having the students sit together and work on problems. She also showed effective use of wait-time by walking away from the students after giving them the problems and giving them some time to work on their own. Also, by going over the topic with a brain dump before giving the students practice problems, the SIL made it easier for the students to actively recall things. This means they could rely on each other more and learning was student-centered. The use of "on a scale of 1-5" was a great way to end the first activity and ensure she knew where the students were, especially since you could see the students were understanding things during the problem solving. The SIL also did an amazing job of redirecting questions to the group to bring them closer to the answer before clearly explaining their mistake or the process to get the answer.

Areas of Improvement:
The majority of the session content focused on practice problems in clusters. This is a very good way to ensure the students are understanding the material, but it may also bore them and not show additional ways the students could study the material. It may also not work for students with different learning styles. The SIL could try to incorporate different kinds of activities. 
There were instances in some problems where one students was solving the other question while the other watched. To ensure they completely understood the answer, the SIL could also ask them to explain the process to get to the answer instead of allowing the one who solved the answer to explain it. This way the SIL could be sure that both understood it.
column33:
Areas of Strength:
The SIL did a great job of being flexible when connecting to the screens wasn't working out by bringing the problems to the students. The activities were entirely student-led and the SIL often had little role in the students finding the answers.

Areas of Improvement:
This is more of a nitpick since the session atmosphere was great. The SIL could try to use the students names when asking them questions to ensure all students are answering.

column36: You do a great job of promoting collaboration and using wait-time to ensure they work more with each other. By leaving the students alone during the activities, you made sure everything was student-led and they were discussing the problems with each other. You also did an amazing job of redirecting questions to the group to bring them closer to the answer before clearly explaining their mistake or the process to get the answer.
column37:
The majority of the session content focused on practice problems in clusters. This is a very good way to ensure the students are understanding the material, but it does not show additional ways the students could study the material and may not work for students with different learning styles. You could try to incorporate different kinds of activities. 
There were instances in some problems where one student was solving the other question while the other watched and agreed with it. To ensure they completely understood the topic, you could also ask them to explain the process to get to the answer instead of allowing the one who solved the answer to explain it. This way you can be sure that both understood it.

column36: SIL - I think that your session was great! column37:
I have two notes for you - one of them being to check for understanding MORE! I heard you say "so does this make sense so far?" to your students a few times - because this is a yes/no question, it is easy for students to just say they understand even if they really don't. Your students did not appear to be super confused (in fact, I thought they did great with the material and asked a lot of really good questions), but regardless, it is still super important to utilize other methods to check for understanding instead of simply asking "does this make sense?" You could maybe try asking your students "hold up a finger 1-5, how do we feel about this material?" during your next session this week.

My second note is that it would be nice to see you utilize a wider variety of collaborative learning techniques! Your session was mostly on one whiteboard, so I was thinking that maybe a gallery walk or something like that might be a good way to get the students thinking on their own or answering each other's questions, something like that. Great job overall though!!

column37: In the future make sure you show up to sessions on time so you can start your session on time and have enough time for all of your activities. It's also an important aspect of professionalism for your image to your students. Additionally, don't forget to write your agenda on the board, and even if you're running late, you still need to include an opener. You mentioned that students came for math so you wanted to get right into it, which I totally understand. You can always include something content related as your opener, like a brain dump, some kind of game with math questions, a review from the last session, or even a challenge question. Also make sure to include a closer, I also am usually running out of time by the end of my session, so I recommend a quick closer like just a check in question - whats something you're looking forward to over the weekend?, whats your favourite ice cream flavour?, etc.

column35: Reminders
column36:
* The SI began the session by checking in with the student and asking what they wanted to focus on, creating a personalized and welcoming start.

* The SI effectively adjusted the activity to fit the student’s needs and maintained a reassuring, relaxed environment that felt like a study session rather than another lecture.

* The students were clearly comfortable; they asked questions freely, and the session felt conversational. In fact, from the brain dump to the queue/stack implementation, it felt like the students were driving the conversation.

* The SI consistently checked for understanding through a variety of methods (drawing, coding smaller sections, discussing edge cases, and allowing the use of notes).

* Something small, but the SI made great use of conceptual connections, linking ADT to encapsulation and abstraction, which helped the student make meaningful connections between new and prior knowledge.

* Led the students through defining concepts, breaking them down, and rebuilding them in a logical way.
column37:
* The SI could hone in on wait time and redirection a bit more. In particular, redirection could be implemented by bouncing one student's question to another. This not only encourages critical thinking but also encourages peer-to-peer discourse. 

* When a new student arrives late, consider integrating them by having the first student explain what’s been covered so far. This can build rapport, serve as a check for understanding, and reinforce the idea of it being a study group. 

* In moments when a question arises that you’re unsure about (e.g., the discussion around size_t), take advantage of redirection by prompting students to explore the concept further:

“What do you think size_t might be used for?”

“Why might the professor prefer this type?”

Have students look up definitions or examples together to promote discovery learning.

column36:
* The SI does an excellent job checking in with students and gauging how they feel about the material. This helps adapt the session to their needs in real time and builds a comfortable, open environment.

* It’s clear that the students have great chemistry and feel at ease participating; they interact, chat, and flow between activities naturally. 

* The spotlight of the session was the use of the SI's facilitation strategies. In particular, the SI's use of wait time was unmatched. They consistently checked for understanding, prompting students to explain their reasoning, make their own definitions, and build on one another's ideas through thoughtful follow-up questions. The SI redirected questions back to students to instigate critical thinking or collaboration to figure out a problem.

* Preparation is evident, as well as overall time management.
column37: There were a few moments when the SI stepped aside from the group for moderate stretches to prepare the next activity. While this worked well for this particular group, for others, it can be important to remain more closely involved with the students throughout the session. Staying engaged even during transitions allows you to observe group dynamics in real time and step in to prompt deeper discussion or introduce new challenges as needed.

column36:
* Created a relaxed and welcoming learning environment. The SI as a whole was very personable and had a great rapport with the students. 

* Promoted collaboration between students. Demonstrated adaptability by noticing when a quieter student participated less and adjusting accordingly. For example, prompting the more shy student with objectives or allowing individual work, then re-grouping and discussing. 

* I was really impressed with the slides. When using slides, it can be easy to turn it into a lecture; the SI, on the other hand, used them more for active recall and checking for understanding (a slide is brief and vague, then has a student use active recall to explain it, then finally has students do an activity relating to the slide to check for understanding) 

* Moved throughout the room frequently to provide individualized support and assess understanding.
column37:
* Could benefit from incorporating more redirection. 

** Instead of directly confirming correctness, ask students to identify or explain their reasoning. The end goal is for students to discover mistakes naturally and correct them naturally to promote critical thinking. 

** With a group that size, it can be helpful to bounce a question around a few times instead of directly answering it. This helps check for understanding (from other students) and promotes collaboration. (don't be afraid of wait time)

* It was evident that this group was much harder to get to collaborate with each other, especially when in clusters. One alternative to this may be to have a much larger group discussion or to do an activity as a class instead. This allows the SI to act as a guide for the conversation. For example, you can bounce questions or ideas around, use wait time until someone speaks, or ask more shy students questions or prompt them to write something directly.

*  There were a few "Does that make sense?" moments. It can feel instinctual to ask this, but 9/10 times, a confused student will simply say yes.

column22:
Areas of Strength:
The SIL did a great job of ensuring the students were all working together by having them sit together and reminding them to discuss when things got silent. When students could not find an answer despite discussing with each other, the SIL had them work through an example/question which allowed them to reach the answer on their own (great use of redirecting/breaking down large concepts without re-lecturing). Instead of asking whether the students understood, he asked what questions they still had which takes the pressure of knowing things away. When students asked him questions, he asked other students if they understood or to help explain things (another point in the redirecting questions column). When students struggled to understand the concept, he led them through parts of it so that they knew enough to understand and then gave the board to the students and stepped away for them to start figuring out an answer. The Kahoot was a great way to check for understanding at the end. The activities had a good range of different study techniques including discussion, practice, and quizzing.
Areas of Improvement:
These are just a nitpick. When the students have questions and none can answer it, have them look at their resources like notes so that they remember how to make use of those while studying. During the group coding, have them all at the board so that you know they're all working together. Otherwise, the student will turn to you with their questions than each other.

The SIL did not have to wait too long for an answer or start calling on people to answer.

* The slides avoid lecturing and promote student interaction

column6:
Marketing:

General Marketing areas were touched on:

* the SI seems to be hitting the core requirements along with promoting sessions in other ways.

*  The idea of using the professor as a method of marketing was discussed, such as having them post announcements on myCourses or promote it during lecture. 

* Likewise, the SI could use a Google Form to collect ideas on why students may or may not be attending. Ways of getting the students to fill out the form were also brought up, such as making a reward for class percentage, putting exam survey questions on it, and having them rank SI activities to promote what happens during sessions.

Other Areas:

One key area that was touched on was how to incorporate a more verbose catalog of openings. 

In general, all classes are different, and some mesh with different types of openings; not all of them have to be personal, such as "Highs and Lows" or "Fun Facts". They can be simple online games such as LinkedIn mini games, Wordle, or GeoGuessr. If you want to get them out of their seats, you could do something like a whiteboard tier list (for example, have them make a marker color tier list with the markers themselves) or draw some squiggles on the board and have them turn them into an animal, such as birds. It's also completely okay for the opening to be content-based, but it should be fairly light and easy to get into (which your openings already seem to be). The main hope is to just get the students out of their seats and interacting/talking with each other.

column37:
* The SI could incorporate some more redirection and checking for understanding into the session to fully grasp comprehension, as it was hard to tell if everyone fully understood some answers. For example, when (or after) having students write an answer on the board, have another student explain the answer. Likewise, throw them a curveball and change the question slightly to see if they fully understand it. 

* While it can be tempting to get a group consensus around understanding, with a group this size, someone is bound to lie or undermine their lack of understanding. So, taking the time to pause and have students summarize key takeaways or misconceptions could ensure everyone stays on track.

* I would have loved to see a bit more redirection, with a group this size and as talkative as they are, having the ability to bounce a question around the room or get different perspectives/phrasings is almost a superpower.

* The SI has a great understanding of the SI model and its nuanced details. His session promoted collaboration, had the students at the whiteboard, and was adaptable to the number of students and the students' needs.

* Used a variety of learning strategies (round robin, clusters, group discussion).

column35: Time complexity review of quicksort
column36:
* Student-centered facilitation: The SI consistently used wait time and guided questioning to help the student discover answers on their own, promoting critical thinking. 

* Breaking problems into manageable parts: The SI did an excellent job scaffolding complex topics like recursion and Big-O by having the student tackle one piece at a time before recombining them into the full solution.

* Active recall integration: The opener with the Big-O cheatsheet was a great way to re-engage prior knowledge. It also physically brought the student up to the board, encouraging active participation.

* Productive dialogue: The session maintained a conversational tone, which always helps strengthen that SI-student dynamic.
column37:
* Clarify conceptual understanding early on: At times, it was difficult to tell whether the student fully understood Big-O or was recalling memorized facts. Consider having them define key terms first, then use examples to reinforce understanding.

* Conceptual Guidance: From my experience, it can be challenging to have students jump right into code. It might help the student more if they first start with more conceptual understanding before jumping into technical. For example, it was unclear if the student fully understood quicksort while coding it. Having them define the process and then drawing out an example promotes both check for understanding and incorporates multiple learning strategies. 

* Enhance facilitation strategies: Certain facilitation strategies could be honed a bit. For example, checking for understanding seemed a bit lacking. Having the student explain their code aloud or predict outcomes can make their reasoning clearer. 

* No agenda: While it's something small, having an agenda on the board can help late comers integrate into the session or even allow students in general to keep track of how the session is progressing.

column22:
Areas of Strength:
You did a great job of using wait-time in letting the students without your input until they were done and redirecting questions by asking questions that forced them to go through what their code would do line-by-line instead to check they understood what they wrote. By having them work at the board, you ensured they would work together. You did a great job checking for their understanding by asking them related questions after checking that their code was correct to ensure they completely understood what they need to do AND why they need to do things in that way.
Areas of Improvement:
This is more of a nitpick. When you ask a group questions, direct some of those questions to specific people so that everyone can show they understand and have a chance to answer.  When you see people start getting stuck on a problem for a bit longer than usual, try to give them a few hints to nudge them in the right direction so you can try to cover more things.
column33:
Areas of Strength:
You did a great job catching the latecomer up on what was going on and integrating them into the activity. By having the students switch who was writing, you made sure everyone participated which was really important in making sure they each showed understanding of the subject.
Areas of Improvement:
I have no points for this.

column9: The session was opened with a formula sheet review where the SIL gave the student access to a document with topic information and gave the student 5 minutes to look over it and ask any questions they may have. This was a great precursor to the Kahoot.
column22:
Areas of Strength:
You showed a good use of wait time during the last activity by giving the student a few minutes to work out the answer on her own before jumping in. You also did a great job of helping the student understand how certain problems needed to be answered and the steps needed to get there through a practice problem which looked like it got through to her more than just telling her the steps would.
Areas of Improvement:
Specifically during the Kahoot activity, you explained the process on how to solve the problem to the student but didn't check that she understood that and moved on to a different type of question once she said she understood. Use similar problems or have the student explain the solution back to you to check that she understands. Use wait time more when giving the student questions to give her time to check her notes or try to find a way to the correct answer on her own first.
It seemed like you wanted to get through all the activities which might have made it difficult for the student to keep up. Focus on making sure the student has enough of an understanding of the topic of one activity before moving to the next, especially if it's important or they'll need that understanding for the next activity. [THE SIL NOTICED AND TOLD ME THIS AFTER].
column33:
Areas of Strength:
The student seemed very comfortable with not knowing and letting you know she didn't understand things which shows the environment of the session was a comfortable one. 
Areas of Improvement:
If the student is struggling to answer something, have them refer to notes or things from class to try to solve the problem on their own before trying to explain it to them. Ask questions to nudge them in the right direction but don't explain the steps to the answer before having them try to use every resource available to them and failing. This will help them remember to make use of those resources and learn how to study independently.
column35: The SIL reminded the student about important things coming up, her next session, and the notes she will send to them.

column9: Code debugging
column22: redirection and wait time we're used but checking for understanding was rarely applied. In particular during the slideshow portion. The SI did keep the student up at the front of the room and kept the session student led.
column33: Very relaxed environment to be in. The SI seems to know this student well and adapted the session to the students areas of strengths and weaknesses in regards to focusing on some activities more then others.
column35: code example
column36:
* Creates a relaxed and comfortable environment where students feel supported and engaged.

* The SI uses effective wait time and redirecting strategies to keep students thinking critically.

* The SI clearly knows where students excel and where they struggle, adapting their approach and the amount of time on each section. 

* Encourages students to come to the board and maintains a very student-centered session.
column37:
* Be sure to post your agenda on the whiteboard. This helps latecomers know what’s happening and supports a clear session structure.

* When students answer a question, ask them to explain or write out their reasoning, whether correct or not, to help check for understanding.

*  It seemed the student was having some trouble during the coding portion. Perhaps try first letting them run through the algorithm from a higher conceptual view. For example, first have the student define what the algorithm is, then run through an example. This can help transition them from the concept to the technical details and provide a variety of learning methods.

* Since you have the room reserved, feel free to ask anyone entering right on the 50 mark for a few minutes to wrap up and clean the space. Oftentimes, if you let one student into the room, you end up letting half the next class in as well.
